Monday July 6th

Motivation

Well start with \(X\) a finite CW complex.

A CW complex is a topological space built by inductively attaching \(i{\hbox{-}}\)dimensional discs (\(i{\hbox{-}}\)cells) \({\mathbb{D}}^i \mathrel{\vcenter{:}}=\left\{{\mathbf{x}\in {\mathbb{R}}^i {~\mathrel{\Big|}~}{\left\lVert {\mathbf{x}} \right\rVert} \leq 1}\right\}\) along their boundary \({{\partial}}{\mathbb{D}}^i = S^{i-1} \mathrel{\vcenter{:}}=\left\{{\mathbf{x}\in {\mathbb{R}}^i {~\mathrel{\Big|}~}{\left\lVert {\mathbf{x}} \right\rVert} = 1}\right\}\).

Define \(\chi(X) = \sum_{i\in {\mathbb{Z}}} (-1)^i {\left\lvert {C_i} \right\rvert}\) where \({\left\lvert {C_i} \right\rvert}\) is the number of \(i{\hbox{-}}\)cells.

Note that a homotopy equivalence between spaces induces an equality between Euler characteristics.

Recall that we can define the cellular chain complex \[\begin{align*} C_*^{\text{cell}}(X, {\mathbb{C}})\mathrel{\vcenter{:}}=\cdots \xrightarrow{{\partial}_{i+1}} C_n^{\text{cell}} (X, {\mathbb{C}}) \xrightarrow{{\partial}_{i}} \cdots \to C_0^{\text{cell}}(X, {\mathbb{C}}) \end{align*}\]

and \(H_i(X, {\mathbb{C}}) \mathrel{\vcenter{:}}=\ker {\partial}_i / \operatorname{im}({\partial})_{i+1}\).

\[\begin{align*} \sum (-1)^i \dim H_i(X, {\mathbb{C}}) = \chi(X) \end{align*}\]

In this sense, cellular homology categorifies the Euler characteristic: weve replaced a set of objects with a category. This is an improvement because we may not have maps between the elements of sets, but we do have maps between objects in a category. We can also talk about things such as functoriality.

The euler characteristic is a weaker invariant than homology. Note that \[\begin{align*} \chi(S^1) = 0 &\quad\text{and}\quad \chi(S^1{\coprod}S^1) = 0 \\ \\ H_0(S^1) = {\mathbb{C}}&\quad\text{while}\quad H_0(S^1{\coprod}S^1) = {\mathbb{C}}\oplus {\mathbb{C}} ,\end{align*}\] so these arent distinguished by euler characteristic alone.

Our first goal will be to assign invariants to oriented links \(L\), where homotopy equivalence will be replaced with isotopy. Well assign a Khovanov complex \(C_*(L,{\mathbb{C}})\), a complex of \({\mathbb{Z}}{\hbox{-}}\)graded \({\mathbb{C}}{\hbox{-}}\)vector spaces, along with the Jones polynomial \(J(L) \in {\mathbb{Z}}[t, t^{-1}]\). By taking the (graded) Euler characteristic of the chain complex, well recover \(J(L)\).

Tuesday July 7th

Recall that we had recursive rules for computing the Kausffman bracket, and a normalization factor for the Jones polynomial that made it into an invariant. Wed like a closed formula for these.

We do this by ordering the crossings of the unoriented link \(1, \cdots, n\), then there is a correspondence \[\begin{align*} \left\{{0, 1}\right\}^n &\iff \text{Complete resolutions} \\ (\alpha_1, \cdots, \alpha_n) &\iff \alpha_i \text{ resolves the $i$th crossing} .\end{align*}\]

\[\begin{align*} \left\langle{D}\right\rangle = \sum_{\alpha \in \left\{{0, 1}\right\}^n} (-1)^{{\left\lvert {\alpha} \right\rvert}} v^{{\left\lvert {\alpha} \right\rvert}} (v+v^{-1})^{c_\alpha(D)} ,\end{align*}\]

where \({\left\lvert {\alpha} \right\rvert}\) is the number of 1-resolutions and \(c_\alpha\) is the number of circles in the resolution corresponding to \(\alpha\).

Idea: look at resolving the \(n\)th crossing locally and apply the recursive relation. Then rewrite the sum by appending \(\alpha_n = 0\) and \(\alpha_n = 1\) respectively. Note that we can rewrite the sum as \[\begin{align*} \sum_{r=0}^n (-1)^r \sum_{{\left\lvert {\alpha } \right\rvert}= r} v^r (v+v^{-1})^{c_\alpha(D)} .\end{align*}\]

This amounts to summing over the columns in the previous diagram:

Here this yields \[\begin{align*} (v+v^{-1})^2 + (-1)2v(v+v^{-1}) + v^2 (v+v^{-1})^2 .\end{align*}\]

Note that this formula starts to resemble an Euler characteristic!

Problem: The coefficient \[\begin{align*} \sum v^r(v+v^{-1})^{c_\alpha(D)} \in {\mathbb{Z}}^{\geq 0}[v, v^{-1}] \end{align*}\] is a Laurent polynomial instead of a natural number, so this cant immediately be interpreted as a dimension of a vector space.

Solution: Replace finite-dimensional \({\mathbb{C}}{\hbox{-}}\)vector spaces by \({\mathbb{Z}}{\hbox{-}}\)graded vector spaces. The category consists of objects given by \(V = \bigoplus_{i\in {\mathbb{Z}}} V_i\) and linear maps \(f:V\to W\) such that \(f(V_i) \subseteq W_i\) for all \(i\).

We previously had vector spaces categorifying the natural numbers by taking the dimension, so for graded vector spaces, we take the graded dimension:

\[\begin{align*} {\operatorname{gr\,dim}}\bigoplus_{i\in{\mathbb{Z}}}V_i = \sum_{i\in {\mathbb{Z}}}\qty{\dim V_i}v^i \in {\mathbb{Z}}^{\geq 0}[v, v^{-1}] .\end{align*}\]

Goal: We want to associate to an oriented link diagram \(D\) a cochain complex of finite-dimensional graded \({\mathbb{C}}{\hbox{-}}\)vector spaces \(C_i(D) \xrightarrow{{{\partial}}} C_{i+1}(D) \to \cdots\). Since each chain space decomposes, the differential does as well, and we get a large collection of chain complexes

This yields two gradings: the first is homological, the second is internal.

We want the following:

  1. If \(D, D'\) are related by a finite sequence of Reidemeister moves, then \[\begin{align*} H_{i, j}(C_{{\,\cdot\,}, {\,\cdot\,}}(D)) = H_{i, j}(C_{{\,\cdot\,}, {\,\cdot\,}}(D')) = \ker {{\partial}}_{i, j} / \operatorname{im}({{\partial}})_{i-1, j} \text{ for all }i, j. \end{align*}\]

  2. Additionally, \[\begin{align*} J(D) = \chi_{{\operatorname{gr}}}(C_{*, *}(D)) = \sum_{i\in {\mathbb{Z}}} (-1)^i {\operatorname{gr\,dim}}\qty{ C_{*, *}(D) } \end{align*}\]

Note that you can also take the dimension of the homology instead, and at the end of the day this yields \(\sum_{i, j\in {\mathbb{Z}}} (-1)^i v^j \dim(H_{i, j})\).

For \(A = \bigoplus A_i, B = \bigoplus B_i\), \(a\in A\) is called homogeneous of degree \(k\) if \(a\in A_k\), i.e.it is a sum of basis elements from only the \(k\)th graded piece. In this case we say \({\left\lvert {a} \right\rvert} = k\).

We can union bases over all graded pieces to get a basis for the entire space.

For direct sums \(A\oplus B\), a basis is given by \((\alpha_i, 0)\) and \((0, \beta_j)\). We put \(\alpha_i\) in degree \({\left\lvert {\alpha_i} \right\rvert}\), in which case \[\begin{align*} {\operatorname{gr\,dim}}(A\oplus B) &= \sum_{k\in {\mathbb{Z}}} \dim(\qty{A\oplus B}_k) v^k \\ &= \sum_k \dim A_k v^k + \sum \dim B_k v^k \\ &= {\operatorname{gr\,dim}}(A) + {\operatorname{gr\,dim}}(B) ,\end{align*}\] so taking direct sums commutes with taking graded dimensions.

Similarly for tensor products \(A\otimes_{\mathbb{C}}B\), we get a basis \(\alpha_i \otimes\beta_j\) placed in degree \({\left\lvert {\alpha_i} \right\rvert} + {\left\lvert {\beta_j} \right\rvert}\).

Show that \[\begin{align*} {\operatorname{gr\,dim}}(A\otimes_{\mathbb{C}}B) = {\operatorname{gr\,dim}}(A) \cdot {\operatorname{gr\,dim}}(B) .\end{align*}\]

We also have degree shifts by \(i\) for any \(i\), denote \(A(i)\), where \(A_j \mapsto A_{j+i}\) for every \(j\). Thus the \(k\)th graded piece is given by \((A(i))_k = A_{k-i}\), thus \[\begin{align*} {\operatorname{gr\,dim}}(A(i)) = v^i {\operatorname{gr\,dim}}(A) \end{align*}\]

\[\begin{align*} H^*(S^2; {\mathbb{C}}) = \begin{cases} {\mathbb{C}}& * = 0, 2 \\ 0 & \text{else}. \end{cases} \end{align*}\]

Let \(A\mathrel{\vcenter{:}}= H^*(S^2; {\mathbb{C}})(-1)\), which now has \({\mathbb{C}}\) in degrees \(\pm 1\), and \({\operatorname{gr\,dim}}A = v + v^{-1}\).

Note that

  • \((v+v^{-1})^2\) corresponds to \(A^{\otimes 2}\).
  • \(2v(v+v^{-1})\) corresponds to \(A(1)^{\oplus 2}\).
  • \(v^2(v+v^{-1})\) corresponds to \(A^{\otimes 2}(2)\).

So we can assemble these into a chain complex and take the Euler characteristic in order to recover the Kauffman bracket in the earlier example.

There exists a unique isotopy invariant of oriented links in \({\mathbb{R}}^3\) called \(P(D) \in {\mathbb{C}}(a, v)\), a rational function in two variables, the HOMFLY-PT polynomial. It satisfies

Yields \[\begin{align*} P(D) = -a(aia^{-1}) + a^2 \qty{a-a^{-1}\over v-v^{-1}}^2 .\end{align*}\]

Wednesday July 8th

Recall that we assigned a chain complex of graded vector spaces to links, where the chains where various tensor powers and shifts of \({\mathcal{A}}\mathrel{\vcenter{:}}= H^*(S^2; {\mathbb{C}})(-1)\). We can consider the diagonal embedding \[\begin{align*} S^s \xrightarrow{\Delta} S^2 \times S^2 \end{align*}\]

which induces maps on both cohomology and homology, and applying the Kunneth formula and the Poincare isomorphism, we get maps \[\begin{align*} m: H^*(S^2)^{\otimes 2} &\to H^*(S^2) \\ \delta: H^*(S^2) &\to H^*(S^2)^{\otimes 2} .\end{align*}\]

We thus get maps \[\begin{align*} m: {\mathbb{C}}[x]/(x^2) \otimes{\mathbb{C}}[x]/(x^2) &\to {\mathbb{C}}[x]/(x^2) \\ \delta: {\mathbb{C}}[x]/(x^2) &\to {\mathbb{C}}[x]/(x^2) \otimes{\mathbb{C}}[x]/(x^2) .\end{align*}\]

See course notes for how to construct differentials out of these, categorifying the bracket, and how to correct with shifts to categorify the Jones polynomial.

Lecture 3

For \(n\geq 1\), the geometric braid \(b\) on \(n\) strands is a topological subspace of \({\mathbb{R}}^2 \times[0, 1]\) such that

  1. \(b \cong {\coprod}_{i=1}^n [0, 1]\) is a homeomorphism
  2. We have \[\begin{align*} b\cap({\mathbb{R}}^2 \times\left\{{0}\right\}) &= \left\{{(1,0,0), \cdots, (n,0,0)}\right\} \\ b\cap({\mathbb{R}}^2 \times\left\{{1}\right\}) &= \left\{{(1,0,1), \cdots, (n,0,1)}\right\} .\end{align*}\]
  3. The projection \({\mathbb{R}}^2 \times[0, 1] \xrightarrow{{\operatorname{pr}}_2}\) maps each strand homeomorphically onto \([0, 1]\).

Braids can be moved via isotopy, and part (c) prevents the following situation:

There is a purely combinatorial description, namely braid diagrams. Isotopies on the geometric side will correspond to planar isotopies and Reidemeister moves R2 and R3 (since R1 is ruled out).

Two braids are isotopic iff their diagrams are related by planar isotopy and a finite sequence of Reidemeister moves.

Define \(B_n\) to be the set of braid diagrams on \(n\) strands up to isotopy and Reidemeister moves, then there is a multiplication given by stacking braid diagrams. This is associative with identity, so we obtain a monoid:

We define elementary braids:

  • \(\left\{{\sigma_i^\pm}\right\}_{i=1}^{n-1}\) generates \(B_n\) as a monoid, so \(\beta \in B_n\) implies \[\begin{align*} \beta = \prod_{k=1}^n \sigma_{i_k}^{\varepsilon_k} \text{ where } i_k \in \left\{{1, \cdots, n-1}\right\} \text{ and }\varepsilon_j \in \left\{{\pm 1}\right\} .\end{align*}\]

  • \(\sigma_i^+ \sigma_i^- = \sigma_i^- \sigma_i^+ = 1\) for all \(i\), thus every braid \(b\) has a two-sided inverse given by reversing the \(\sigma_{i_k}\)s and swapping \(\pm\), so \(B_n\) is a group.

We can describe this group completely algebraically as \(B_n^{\text{Artin}}\), the group generated by \(\left\{{\sigma_i}\right\}_{i=1}^{n-1}\) with relations \[\begin{align*} \sigma_i \sigma_j &= \sigma_j \sigma_i && \text{for } {\left\lvert {i-j} \right\rvert} \geq 2 \\ \sigma_i \sigma_{i+1} \sigma_i &= \sigma_{i+1} \sigma_i \sigma_{i+1} && \text{for } i\in \left\{{1, \cdots, n-2}\right\} .\end{align*}\]

There is an isomorphism \[\begin{align*} B_n^{\text{Artin}} &\xrightarrow{\cong} B_n \\ \sigma_i &\mapsto \sigma_i^+ \\ \sigma_i^{-1}&\mapsto \sigma_i^- .\end{align*}\]

Well defined: Need to check that the map preserves the relations, this is a consequence of changing height of crossings by planar isotopy:

  • Surjectivity: clear by definition of map.

  • Injectivity: omitted.

Importantly, we have a way of going from braids to knots and links. Let \(D^{\text{or}}\) be the set of oriented planar link diagrams, then define a map \[\begin{align*} B_n &\to D^{\text{or}} \\ b &\mapsto \widehat{b} \end{align*}\]

where \(\widehat{b}\) is given by closing the braid:

Every oriented link in \({\mathbb{R}}^3\) is isotopic to a closed braid.

In fact, there is a map \[\begin{align*} {\coprod}_{n\geq 1} &\twoheadrightarrow D^{\text{or}} /\sim \\ b & \mapsto \widehat{b} \end{align*}\]

where the RHS is the equivalence relation generated by planar isotopy and Reidemeister moves. This is not injective, since many braids can map onto the unknot.

Thursday July 9th

Problem: the map sending links to the Artin braid group is surjective but not injective, so we need to mod out by some form of equivalence in the domain.

We have a directed system of inclusions \(B_n \hookrightarrow B_{n+1}\), so we can consider the group \({\coprod}_{n\geq 1} B_n\). The equivalence relation well take is Markov equivalence \(\sim_M\):

\(b \sim_M b' \iff ?\)

For the reverse direction

For the forward direction, see Kassel-Tuvaevs Braid Groups for a full rigorous proof.

For any set \(E\), a Markov function is a family of maps \(\left\{{f_n: B_n \to E}\right\}_{n\geq 1}\) such that

  1. \(f_n(\alpha \beta) = f_n(\beta\alpha)\) for all \(\alpha, \beta\in B_n\)

  2. \(f_{n+1}(i_n(\beta)\sigma_n^{-1}) = f_n(\beta) = f_{n+1}(i_n(\beta) \sigma_n)\) for all \(n\geq, \beta \in B_n\).

Question: where does the skein relation come from?

Take \({\mathbb{F}}_q\) a finite field of size \(q\) and set \(G = \operatorname{GL}(n, {\mathbb{F}}_q)\). Define \(C(G) = \left\{{G\to {\mathbb{C}}}\right\}\) which is a \({\mathbb{C}}{\hbox{-}}\)vector space with an associative multiplication given by \[\begin{align*} (f\ast f')(g) \mathrel{\vcenter{:}}=\sum_{n\in G} f(n) f'(n^{-1}g) \end{align*}\]

Define \[\begin{align*} C\qty{% {\textstyle B} \mkern-4mu\scalebox{1.5}{$\diagdown$}\mkern-5mu^{\textstyle G}% \mkern-4mu\scalebox{1.5}{$\diagup$}\mkern-5mu{\textstyle B} } = \left\{{f: G\to {\mathbb{C}}{~\mathrel{\Big|}~}f(bg) = f(g) = f(gb)}\right\} \end{align*}\] the set of bi-invariant functions. This is closed under \(\ast\) with a unit defined by setting \[\begin{align*} \delta_g(h) &= \indic{h=g} \\ \delta_0 &= {1\over {\left\lvert {B} \right\rvert}} \sum_{g\in B} \delta_g .\end{align*}\]

There is an augmentation map \[\begin{align*} \varepsilon: \qty{% {\textstyle B} \mkern-4mu\scalebox{1.5}{$\diagdown$}\mkern-5mu^{\textstyle G}% \mkern-4mu\scalebox{1.5}{$\diagup$}\mkern-5mu{\textstyle B} } &\to {\mathbb{C}}\\ f &\mapsto \sum_{g\in G} f(g) \in {\mathbb{C}} .\end{align*}\] which is a \({\mathbb{C}}{\hbox{-}}\)algebra morphism. Can we write down a basis?

Recall that the symmetric group is generated by adjacent transpositions, say \(s_1, \cdots, s_{n-1}\), so we can write \[\begin{align*} S_n \cong \left\langle{\mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mus\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu_1, \cdots, \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mus\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu_{n-1} {~\mathrel{\Big|}~}\mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mus\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu_i^2 = 1, \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mus\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu_i \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mus\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu_j = \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mus\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu_j \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mus\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu_i, \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mus\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu_i \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mus\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu_{i+1} \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mus\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu_i = \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mus\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu_{i+1} \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mus\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu_i \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mus\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu_{i+1} }\right\rangle .\end{align*}\]

Need to check that elements in \(S_n\) satisfy these relations, check cardinality, etc.

For any \(w\in S_n\), we can consider its length \(\ell(w)\) defined as the smallest number of adjacent transpositions need to write \(w\) as a product of adjacent transpositions. We define the Bruhat cell \(B w B \mathrel{\vcenter{:}}=\left\{{bwb^{-1}{~\mathrel{\Big|}~}b, b' \in B}\right\}\) where \(B\) is a permutation matrix for \(w\).

The functions \[\begin{align*} \delta_w: G &\to {\mathbb{C}}\\ \delta_w(g) &= {1\over {\left\lvert {B} \right\rvert}}\indic{g\in BwB} \end{align*}\] as \(w\) ranges over \(S_n\) form a basis for \(\qty{% {\textstyle B} \mkern-4mu\scalebox{1.5}{\)\(}\mkern-5mu^{\textstyle G}% \mkern-4mu\scalebox{1.5}{\)\(}\mkern-5mu{\textstyle B} }\).

Use the Bruhat decomposition \(G = {\coprod}_{w\in S_n} BwB\).

Multiplicative Structure

There is a multiplicative structure, since \[\begin{align*} (\delta_{s_i} \ast \delta_{s_i})(g) &\mathrel{\vcenter{:}}=\sum_{h\in G} \delta_{s_i}(h) \delta_{s_i}(h^{-1}g) \\ &= \sum_{h\in Gs_i B} {1\over {\left\lvert {B} \right\rvert}} \delta_{s_i} (h^{-1}g) \\ \\ &= \sum_{\substack{ h\in S }} {1\over {\left\lvert {B} \right\rvert}^2} && S = \left\{{h\in B_{s_i} B ~{\text{s.t.}}~h^{-1} g \in B_{s_i} B}\right\} \\ &= {{\left\lvert {Bs_i B \cap gBs_i B} \right\rvert} \over {\left\lvert {B} \right\rvert}^2} .\end{align*}\]

To express this in terms of our basis, check where \(B_si B \cap g B s_i B \neq \emptyset\). If \(h\) is in this intersection, then \(h = bs_i b = gb'' s_i b'''\), so \[\begin{align*} g = b s_i b' (b''')^{-1}s_i (b'')^{-1}\in Bs_i Bs_i B \subset P_i \end{align*}\] where \(P_i\) is a parabolic subgroup of \(G\) defined by

We can identify \(P_i = Bs_i B \cup B\) (i.e.add in upper triangular matrices). We can thus write \(\delta_{s_i} \ast \delta_{s_i} = \alpha \delta_{s_i} + \beta \delta_0\) where \(\delta_0 = \delta_e\) and \(\alpha, \beta \in {\mathbb{C}}\).

Let \(\bbone\) be the identity matrix, then

\[\begin{align*} {{\left\lvert {B s_i B} \right\rvert} \over {\left\lvert {B} \right\rvert}^2} = (\delta_{s_i} \ast \delta_{s_i}) (\bbone) = \alpha \delta_{s_i} + \beta \delta_0(\bbone) .\end{align*}\]

where the first term is in \(B\) and thus equals zero, and the second term equals \(1\over {\left\lvert {B} \right\rvert}\), so this equals \(\beta{1\over {\left\lvert {B} \right\rvert}}\), thus \(\beta = {{\left\lvert {Bs_i B} \right\rvert} \over {\left\lvert {B} \right\rvert} }\). Similarly, we get \(\alpha = {{\left\lvert {Bs_i B} \right\rvert} \over {\left\lvert {B} \right\rvert}} - 1\).

A counting argument shows \[\begin{align*} {\left\lvert {B} \right\rvert} = (q-1)^n q q^2 \cdots q^{n-1} = (1-1)^n q^{n(n-1) \over 2} .\end{align*}\]

Similarly \[\begin{align*} {\left\lvert {Bs_i B} \right\rvert} = (q-1)^n q^{{n(n-1) \over 2} + 1} \implies {{\left\lvert {Bs_i B} \right\rvert} \over {\left\lvert {B} \right\rvert}} = 1 .\end{align*}\] Thus \[\begin{align*} (\delta_{s_i} \ast \delta_{s_i}) = (q-1) \delta_{s_i} + q\delta_0 .\end{align*}\]

In particular, \(\delta_{s_i}\) is a unique with inverse \(q^{-1}\delta_{s_i} - (1-q^{-1}) \delta_0\).

More generally, for \(s_i \in S_n, w\in S_n\) with \(\ell(s_i w) > \ell(w)\), we have \(\delta_{s_i} \ast \delta_w = \delta_{s_i w}\).

Omitted, see Bump Hecke Algebras.

Upshot: we have a group morphism \[\begin{align*} \phi: B_n &\to C\qty{% {\textstyle B} \mkern-4mu\scalebox{1.5}{$\diagdown$}\mkern-5mu^{\textstyle G}% \mkern-4mu\scalebox{1.5}{$\diagup$}\mkern-5mu{\textstyle B} }^{\times}\\ \sigma_i &\mapsto \delta_{s_i} .\end{align*}\]

Friday July 10th

The Iwahori-Hecke Algebra

For \(n\geq 1\) and \(R\) a commutative ring with \(q,z \in R^{\times}\), define the Iwahori-Hecke algebra \(H_n^R(q, z)\) is the associative unital \(R{\hbox{-}}\)algebra \[\begin{align*} \left\langle{T_i {~\mathrel{\Big|}~}R}\right\rangle \text{where the relations $R$ are defined by } \\ T_i T_j &= T_j T_i && {\left\lvert {i - j} \right\rvert} \geq 2 \\ T_i T_{i+1} T_i &= T_{i+1} T_i T_{i+1} \\ T_i^2 &= zT_i q1 \end{align*}\] where \(1\) is the unit of the algebra. The first relation is the braid relation, the other two are quadratic or skein relations.

  1. For all \(w \in S_n\), there exists a unique \(T_w\in H_n^R(q, z)\) such that whenever \(w = \prod s_{i_k}\) is a minimal expression as a product of simply transpositions, then \(T_w = \prod T_{i_k}\).
  2. The set \(\left\{{T_w {~\mathrel{\Big|}~}w\in S_n}\right\}\) is an \(R{\hbox{-}}\)module basis of \(H_n^R(q, z)\) (the standard basis).

A category \({\mathcal{A}}\) is additive iff

  1. The homs \({\mathcal{A}}(X, Y)\) is a \({\mathbb{Z}}{\hbox{-}}\)module for all \(X, Y\in {\mathcal{A}}\)
  2. \({\mathcal{A}}(X, Y) \times{\mathcal{A}}(Y, Z) \to {\mathcal{A}}(X, Z)\) where \((f, g) \mapsto g\circ f\) is \({\mathbb{Z}}{\hbox{-}}\)bilinear.
  3. \(\exists 0\in {\mathcal{A}}\), an object that is both initial and terminal.
  4. For all \(X, Y\in {\mathcal{A}}\), there exists a coproduct \(X\oplus Y\)

Recall that an object \(I\) is initial in \(A\) iff for every \(X\) there exists a unique \(I\to X\), and terminal iff there exists a unique \(X\to I\).

Recall that a coproduct of \(X, Y\) is an object \(X\oplus Y\) with two morphism \(\iota_X: X\to X\oplus Y, \iota_Y: Y\to X\oplus Y\) satisfying the appropriate universal property.

\(R{\hbox{-}}\)bimodules over \(R\) a ring.

An additive category \({\mathcal{A}}\) is essentially small iff the isoclasses \([X]\) of objects form a set.

Assume \({\mathcal{A}}\) is additive and essentially small. Then we can define a free abelian group on \[\begin{align*} F({\mathcal{A}}) \mathrel{\vcenter{:}}=\left\{{[X] {~\mathrel{\Big|}~}X\in {\mathcal{A}}}\right\} \end{align*}\] along with a subgroup \[\begin{align*} N({\mathcal{A}}) \mathrel{\vcenter{:}}=\left\{{[X\oplus Y] - [X] - [Y]}\right\} .\end{align*}\] Define the split Grothendieck group as the following: \[\begin{align*} K_0^\oplus \mathrel{\vcenter{:}}= F(A) / N(A) \end{align*}\]

Note that this starts to look like categorification: we can express direct sums in terms of sums in a module. Notation: mod denotes finitely generated, Mod denotes full categories.

\({\mathcal{A}}= k{\hbox{-}}\)mod, the category of finite-dimensional \(k{\hbox{-}}\)vector spaces. There is a well-defined group morphism defined on generators \[\begin{align*} \phi: F({\mathcal{A}}) &\twoheadrightarrow{\mathbb{Z}}\\ [V] &\mapsto \dim_k(V) \end{align*}\] which is surjective since \(-[V]\) exists in the domain and \([k^n] \mapsto n\) for all \(n\).

Note that this will factor through \(K_0^\oplus({\mathcal{A}}) = F({\mathcal{A}})/ N({\mathcal{A}})\) via a map \(\mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mu\phi\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu\) iff \(N({\mathcal{A}}) \subseteq \ker \phi\). We can check \[\begin{align*} \phi\qty{[V\oplus W] - [V] - [W] } = \dim(V\oplus W) - \dim(V) - \dim(W) = 0 .\end{align*}\]

\(\phi\) is actually injective.

Suppose \[\begin{align*} 0 = \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mu\phi\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu\qty{ \sum \lambda_i [V_i]} = \sum \lambda_i \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mu\phi\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu([V_i]) = \sum \lambda_i \dim(V_i) .\end{align*}\]

We can now check \[\begin{align*} \sum \lambda_i [V_i] = \sum \lambda_i \dim(V_i) [k] = [k] \sum \lambda_i \dim(V_i) ,\end{align*}\] where we use the fact that if \(\dim V = n\), then \([V] = [k^n] = n[k]\).

Let \(G\) be an abelian group, then \({\mathcal{A}}\) categorifies \(G\) iff \(K_0^\oplus({\mathcal{A}}) \cong G\).

A monoidal category is a tuple \(({\mathcal{C}}, {\,\cdot\,}\otimes{\,\cdot\,}, 1, \alpha, \ell, r)\) such that

  • \({\mathcal{C}}\) is a category
  • \({\,\cdot\,}\otimes{\,\cdot\,}: {\mathcal{C}}\times{\mathcal{C}}\to {\mathcal{C}}\) is a bifunctor.
  • \(1\in {\mathcal{C}}\)
  • Natural isomorphisms \[\begin{align*} \alpha_{X,Y,Z}: (X\otimes Y)\otimes Z \xrightarrow{\cong} X\otimes(Y\otimes Z) \end{align*}\] for all \(X,Y,Z\in {\mathcal{C}}\) (associators).
  • Natural isomorphisms \[\begin{align*} \ell_X: 1\otimes X &\xrightarrow{\cong} X\\ r_X:X\otimes 1 &\xrightarrow{\cong}X \end{align*}\] and for all \(X\in {\mathcal{C}}\).

Along with coherence axioms: for all \(W,X,Y,Z\in {\mathcal{C}}\),

If \({\mathcal{C}}\) is additive, we require \({\,\cdot\,}\otimes{\,\cdot\,}\) to be biadditive, i.e.\(X\otimes{\,\cdot\,}\) and \({\,\cdot\,}\otimes Y\) are additive functors. We have an isomorphism of \(R{\hbox{-}}\)bimodules satisfying the desired relations.

\(R\cong R^{s_i}(2) \oplus R^{s_i}\) as graded \(R^{s_i}{\hbox{-}}\)bimodules.

It suffices to show that every \(f\in R\) can be written uniquely as \[\begin{align*} f = g(x_i - x_{i+1}) + h \text{ with } g, h \in R^{s_i} .\end{align*}\]

Uniqueness: If \(f =g'(x_i - x_{i+1}) + h'\) then \[\begin{align*} g'(2x_i - 2x_{i+1}) &= f - s_i f \\ &= g(x_i - x_{i+1}) - g(x_{i+1} - x_i) \\ &= g(x_i - x_{i+1} - x_{i+1} + x_i) \\ &= g(2x_i - 2x_{i+1}) .\end{align*}\]

Since this is an integral domain, \(g=g'\), and \[\begin{align*} h = f - g (x_i - x_{i+1}) = f - g'(x_i - x_{i+1}) = h' .\end{align*}\]

Existence: \(x_k \in R^{s_i}\) is \(s_i\) invariant if \(k\neq i, i+1\), and \[\begin{align*} x_i = {1\over 2}\qty{ x_i - x_{i+1}} + {1\over 2}\qty{x_i + x_{i+1}} \in R^{s_i} \qty{\cdots} + R^{s_i} \\ x_{i+1} = -{1\over 2}\qty{ x_i - x_{i+1}} + {1\over 2}\qty{x_i + x_{i+1}} \in R^{s_i} \qty{\cdots} + R^{s_i} \\ .\end{align*}\]

So every \(f\in R\) can be expressed as a polynomial in \(x_i - x_{i+1}\) with coefficients in \(R^{s_i}\). Since \(\qty{x_i - x_{i+1}}^2 \in R^{s_i}\), any polynomial in \(x_i - x_{i+1}\) with coefficients in \(R^{s_i}\) can be written as \(g(x_i - x_{i+1}) + h\) with \(g, h \in R^{s_i}\). This proves the claim.

We can now check \[\begin{align*} B_{s_i} \otimes_R B_{s_i} &= \qty{R \otimes_{R^{s_i}} R} \otimes_R \qty{R \otimes_{R^{s_i}} R}(-2) \\ &\cong R \otimes_{R^{s_i}} R \otimes_{R^{s_i}} R(-2) \\ &\cong R \otimes_{R^{s_i}} \qty{ R^{s_i}(2) \oplus R^{s_i} } \otimes_{R^{s_i}} R(-2) \\ &\cong R \otimes_{R^{s_i}} \qty{ R^{s_i}(2) } \otimes_{R^{s_i}} R(-2) \oplus R \otimes_{R^{s_i}} \qty{ R^{s_i} } \otimes_{R^{s_i}} R(-2) \\ &\cong R \otimes_{R^{s_i}} R \oplus R\otimes_{R^{s_i}} R(-2) \\ &\cong B_{s_i}(1) \oplus B_{s_i}(-1) .\end{align*}\]

Soergels Dream

Come up with a purely algebraic proof of the KL conjecture (without using machinery from geometric representation theory). Consider the center of category \(O\), \(Z({\mathcal{O}}_0)\), the endomorphism ring of the identity functor. It can be shown that this is isomorphic to the coinvariant ring \({\mathbb{C}}[x_1, \cdots, x_{n+1}] / {\mathbb{C}}[x_1, \cdots, x_{n+1}]^{S^n}\). Thus invariant theory is hidden in the category \({\mathcal{O}}_0({\mathfrak{g}})\).

Question: What is the category \({\mathcal{A}}\)?

Take \(R{\hbox{-}}{\operatorname{gr\,dim}}\), the category of graded \(R{\hbox{-}}\)bimodules, which is finitely generated as both left/right \(R{\hbox{-}}\)modules. This is additive, monoidal, and graded, but this category is too big. So we carve out a smaller subcategory.

For \(w\in S_n\), write the formal word \(\mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5muw\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu = s_{i_1} \cdots s_{i_r}\) a reduced expression for \(w\). Note that this depends on which reduced expression is used. Now define \[\begin{align*} BS(\mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5muw\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu) &\mathrel{\vcenter{:}}=\bigotimes^{j\leq r}{}_{R^{s_{i_j}}} \,\,B_{s_{i_j}} && BS(\emptyset) = R \\ &\cong R \otimes_{R^{s_{i_1}}} R \otimes\cdots \otimes_{R^{s_{i_r}}} R \end{align*}\] where the isomorphism is canonical. This is the Bott-Samelson bimodule.

  • A Soergel bimodule is a direct summand of a finite sum of grading shifts of Bott-Samelson bimodules.
  • The category \(\mathbf{SBim}\) of Soergel bimodules is the strictly full subcategory of \(R{\hbox{-}}{\operatorname{gr\,dim}}\) consisting of Soergel bimodules.
  • Equivalently, the smallest full subcategory of \(R{\hbox{-}}{\operatorname{gr\,dim}}\) consisting of \(R, B_{s_i}\) and closed under \(\otimes_R, \oplus, (i)\) and taking direct summands.

The category \(\mathbf{SBim}\) is additive, monoidal, and graded, but not abelian.

Recall that a module \(X\) is indecomposable \(\iff\) \(X \cong A\oplus B\) implies \(A\cong 0\) or \(B\cong 0\).

A category \(\mathcal{C}\) is Krull-Schmidt \(\iff\) every object decomposes uniquely into a finite direct sum of indecomposable objects.

  1. \(\mathbf{SBim}\) is Krull-Schmidt.

Note that such uniqueness here means that if \(\bigoplus_{i=1}^r X_i \cong \bigoplus_{i=1}^s Y_i\) then \(r=s\) and there is some permutation \(\pi \in S_r\) such that \(X_{\pi(i)} \cong Y_i\).

  1. There is a bijection \[\begin{align*} S_n &\rightleftharpoons\left\{{\substack{\text{Indecomposable Soergel bimodules} }}\right\}/ \text{\tiny Isomorphism and shifts} \\ w &\mapsto B_w .\end{align*}\]

Moreover \(\left\{{ S[B_w] {~\mathrel{\Big|}~}w\in S_n }\right\}\) form a basis of \(K_0^\oplus(\mathbf{SBim})\) as \({\mathbb{Z}}[v, v^{-1}]{\hbox{-}}\)modules.

  1. There is a \({\mathbb{Z}}[v, v^{-1}]{\hbox{-}}\)algebra morphism \[\begin{align*} c: {\mathcal{H}}(S_n) &\xrightarrow{\cong} K_0^\oplus(\mathbf{SBim}) \\ C_{s_i} &\mapsto [B_{s_i}] .\end{align*}\]

This implies both the KL positivity and multiplicity conjectures. The KL basis corresponds to the basis given by the indecomposable Soergel bimodules.

For \(A\in \text{mod}{\hbox{-}}{\mathbb{Z}}\), \(A\) is torsionfree \(\iff \text{Tor}_1^{\mathbb{Z}}(A, B) = 0\) for every other \(B\in {\mathbb{Z}}{\hbox{-}}\text{mod}\). There is an isomorphism of categories \[\begin{align*} R\otimes_R R^\text{op}{\hbox{-}}\text{mod} &\xrightarrow{\cong} R{\hbox{-}}\text{bimod} \\ (r_1\otimes r_2) \cdot m &\mapsfrom r_1 \cdot m \cdot r_2 \in RMR .\end{align*}\]

The point of this is that we may not be able to make sense of projective resolutions on the RHS, but we can think of them as usual modules over the enveloping algebra instead.

Some care must be taken with the monoidal structure. The monoidal structur in the LHS is \(\otimes_{R\otimes_R R^\text{op}}\), whereas it is \(\otimes_R\) in the RHS.

Define the \(i\)th Hochschild homology of \(R\) as the functor \[\begin{align*} HH_i(R, {\,\cdot\,}) \mathrel{\vcenter{:}}=\text{Tor}_i^{R\otimes_R R^\text{op}}(R, {\,\cdot\,}) : R{\hbox{-}}\text{Bimod} &\to k{\hbox{-}}\text{mod} .\end{align*}\]

Note that this lands in \(k{\hbox{-}}\)modules instead of \({\mathbb{Z}}{\hbox{-}}\)modules. Moreover, everything works in the graded setting and yields a functor \(R{\hbox{-}}\text{grBimod} \to k{\hbox{-}}\text{grMod}\).
